default6. defaultThe Big Four, two of which are Irish owned and two of which are internationally owned, have traditionally played the largest role in the market. However, the banking sector in Northern Ireland has undergone significant change in recent years. Some of the n
defaultewer international entrants to the market include HSBC Bank 
defaultplc.,
default Barclays Bank plc., both headquartered in London; Santander UK plc., a wholly owned by the Spanish Santander Group, headquartered in Spain; and Halifax plc., a wholly owned subsidiary of Llo
defaultyds Banking Group headquartered in London. 
default7. defaultThe following describes the structure of the mortgage lending processes adopted by banks operating in Northern Ireland. Traditionally, banks in Northern Ireland operated under a decentralised model whereby, b
defaultranch managers had local discretions of varying amounts that enabled them to make loans up to a certain value so long as they complied with head office credit policy. With recent technological advancement, the study investigated the impact of these develop
defaultments on the mortgage decision making process. 
default8. defaultOur findings suggest that three of the banks that participated in the study have adopted a centralised mortgage lending process whereby all mortgages are reviewed and sanctioned from one central location.
default For these banks in the sample, the location of their centralised credit functions is also either Belfast or England. In the case of one of the banks, this model was adopted over a decade ago but for the others this change had occurred more recently and in
default the majority of cases was implemented after the crisis of 2007. Prior to 2007, each of these banks operated under a decentralised model.
default9. defaultThe findings of the study also indicate that currently two of the international banks that participated in the stu
defaultdy operate under a mixed model of centralisation and decentralisation. These banks have always operated under such a structure and currently have no plans to change the model. Under this approach, certain products are reviewed centrally but in general mort
defaultgages continue to be assessed under a decentralised model with branch managers retaining local discretion.
default 
defaultFor these banks, the location of their centralised credit functions is either Belfast or England.
default10. defaultThe level of IT that is used within the proc
defaultess varies among all the banks. One of the banks has implemented an automated and largely standardised system whereas others have adopted systems of a more bespoke nature. Regardless of the model adopted however, there is still scope for internal change an
defaultd there is still a large element of judgement based evaluation of applications. 
default&#xa0;defaultIs there any disadvantage for customers, both private and business, in NI as a result?default11. defaultIn terms of the general structure of the banking system in Northern Ireland, the mi
defaultxture of domestic and international banks in the current climate can be viewed as advantageous. Non-Irish banks with wider access to funding from their overall group and parent banks may be more willing to lend. In addition, consumers have access to more p
defaultroduct choice and may enjoy more favourable rates. 
default12. defaultSpecifically in regard to the mortgage lending process, preliminary findings indicate that centralised decision making has both advantages and disadvantages. The disadvantages include less negotiatio
defaultn at the local level, a lack of local knowledge and in some instances understanding of the market and decision making is often slower. There are also often wider economic implications in terms of the reduced number of branches and staff required to operate
default in the area.
default 
defaultHowever, the centralised model also offers a number of advantages. These include the ability to achieve economies of scale and thereby reduce costs. In addition, the specialisation of knowledge that is associated with centralisation raises q
defaultuality and standards and is seen to result in independent and consistent decision making. 
defaultDo banks that operate in both GB and NI, e.g. Barclays and Santander, operate differently in Northern Ireland than in the rest of the UK? Does this result in customdefaulters in NI being at a disadvantage compared to customers in GB?default13. defaultNo comment. The study examined Northern Ireland only. 
defaultWhat are the consequences for customers in NI of banks and bank debts being owned by non-UK banks?default14. defaultThere are implications due to 
defaultthe lack of control over the behaviour of these institutions, particularly in relation to their asset disposal strategy (see below for further details). There are also regulatory implications. 
defaultWhat role does the Republic of Ireland play in NI banking?default15default. defaultAs outlined above, officially the Republic of Ireland plays a relatively small role in Northern Ireland banking. Although some of the institutions operating in Northern Ireland, are foreign owned, in theory they operate under the UK regulatory framework.
default However, there may be an impact in terms of the different cultural and operating environments of the parent banks headquartered in other jurisdictions. As subsidiaries, the conditions imposed on some of the banks as a result of state support, specifically
default those incorporated in the Republic of Ireland could also lead to restrictions on their activities in Northern Ireland.
default 
defaultWhat effect does the sale of bank assets by NAMA have on NI property values?default16. defaultAll property developers and banks that participated
default in the study were questioned on the perceived impact of NAMA on the Northern Ireland market.
default 
defaultThere was a general feeling among respondents that the sale of bank assets by NAMA has created a negative perception in the market place which may be hindering r
defaultecovery. While some respondents initially regarded the concept of NAMA as a positive move, the actual performance of NAMA in relation to the disposal of assets situated in Northern Ireland, was repeatedly questioned. The issue of whether NAMA is ‘drip feed
defaulting’ the market was also raised. Respondents felt that there was an incentive for potential buyers to delay purchasing, as NAMA still holds a substantial proportion of assets in the market that must be disposed of within its limited lifespan.
default17. defaultOther respondents, mainly property developers, commended NAMA for its long term view towards asset disposal unlike other institutions. One interviewee commented on how NAMA was the ‘best place to be’ at present. However, concerns were raised over the futur
defaulte strategy of NAMA as it was felt that to date, they had disposed of ‘all the low hanging fruit’ in order to achieve targets. In general, the lack of transparency over NAMA's activities and future strategy has created a feeling of insecurity among those in
defaultvolved with the organisation.
default 
default18. defaultThe behaviour of financial institutions with large property debt exposures, other than NAMA, was also raised. Thus, it is not only the sale of assets by NAMA that is impacting on Northern Ireland property values. There 
defaultwas a general feeling among those involved with Ulster Bank that it has been more aggressive in attempting to recoup losses. The uncertainty over Ulster Banks future was also highlighted as a source of constant concern and confusion for respondents.
