default&#xa0;defaultThe lack of effectiveness of national initiatives to help aid economic recoverydefaultIs the population of NI at a disadvantage to the rest of the UK as a result of the lack of uptake of national economic recovery idefaultnitiatives by banks in NI?default27. defaultWhile Northern Ireland has experienced a much deeper and prolonged recession in comparison to other areas of the UK, there is little evidence to suggest that this was a result of the lack of uptake of national economic recove
defaultry initiatives by banks operating in Northern Ireland. It is however, important to consider that these banks are often influenced by polices of state regulators in which their headquarters are located.
default 
defaultIf so, is a more tailored approach from the HM Treadefaultsury required for NI? default28. defaultNo, economic recovery is a challenge facing all of the UK; it is not solely a regional issue.
defaultAccess to banking in rural communitiesdefaultFollowing the closure of defaultDanskedefault Bank of some branches in rural areas, are the interests of thosdefaulte living in more rural areas, particularly the elderly, sufficiently fulfilled by the banking structure as it currently stands? How significantly will the situation be exacerbated if Ulster Bank also closes some of its rural branches?default29. defaultNorthern Ireland 
defaulthas a different demographic profile and a lower degree of urbanisation than other parts of Great Britain and as such the delivery of banking services in rural areas is a general issue. While anecdotal evidence suggests that the needs of the elderly may not
default be sufficiently fulfilled by the banking structure currently, there is no easy solution. 
default30. defaultThe role of the branch network has changed in recent years. Technological advancement and changing consumer behaviour have been key drivers of this change. Tech
defaultnology adoption is slower within the elderly cohort of the population and in general, rural areas can be considered more conservative.
default 
default31. defaultThe implications of recent changes to the branch network in Northern Ireland and of any further projected changes 
defaultis that new delivery channels tailored to the needs of the elderly may be required. However, substitutes to the branch network can be implemented.
defaulto
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultExtend the services currently provided through the Post Office
defaultIt is estimated that 95% of the total rural 
defaultpopulation across the UK are within three miles of their nearest outlet. More specifically, within Northern Ireland there are currently 331 post offices located in rural areas. The services currently offered are primarily traditional intermediation functio
defaultns such as deposition taking however, these are not available at all locations. These services if expanded offer a potential avenue that may assist in overcoming the access issues for the rural population that are currently being raised.
defaulto
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIncrease the serv
defaultices that Credit Unions are permitted to provide
defaultAs highlighted by the Department of Enterprise, Trade and Investment, an update of the legislation on credit unions in Northern Ireland to increase the services that they are permitted to provide, could pote
defaultntially act as a another countermeasure to the rural branch closures.
default 
defaultAround 23.6% of the 
defaultp
defaultopulation in Northern Ireland 
defaultis a member
default of a credit union compared to only 1.6% in Great Britain (
defaultMcKillop
default, Ward and Wilson 2010). An increase of powers to credit unions may increase competition within the sector and in the delivery of services to rural areas.
defaulto
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUse banking Kiosks as an alternat
defaultive off site delivery channel
defaultAnother alternative as outlined by Jim Brown, the Chief Executive of the Ulster Bank Group, includes the use of kiosks for rural areas. These provide several locations for customers to access services without requiring the sam
defaulte level of investment that would be necessary to sustain a rural branch. This substitute does however; require the largest change in consumer 
defaultbehaviour
default. There is therefore, the need to implement support mechanisms for this transition and to further educate
default consumers in this regard. 
default32. defaultOverall, while the decline of the branch network is challenging for rural areas, the main issues are age and education sensitive. 
defaultO
defaultn one hand there is scope for the expansion of existing services or development of alternati
defaultves such as those outlined above. On the other hand, with the level of adoption of currently available online and mobile banking facilities increasing, the costs involved in implementing the alternatives must be carefully considered. 
